🔑 DSA Pattern / Concept
Pattern: Greedy + Sorting
Why?
Each hill height can be adjusted by either +k or -k.
We want to minimize the difference between the tallest and shortest hills.
The trick is to sort the array and then consider how shifting the “cut point” changes the min/max.

  ---------------------------------------------------
🧩 Algorithm
Sort the array nums.
Initial difference = nums.back() - nums.front().
For each index i from 0 to n‑2:
Imagine splitting the array at i.
Left side hills (≤ i) are increased by k.
Right side hills (> i) are decreased by k.
Compute new min and max:
high = max(nums[i] + k, nums.back() - k)
low = min(nums[0] + k, nums[i+1] - k)
Update answer = min(answer, high - low).
Return the minimum difference.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

int smallestRangeII(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        int n = nums.size();
        sort(nums.begin(), nums.end());
        int res = nums.back()-nums.front();

        for(int i = 0 ; i<n-1 ; i++){
            int high = max(nums[i]+k, nums.back()-k);
            int low = min(nums[0]+k , nums[i+1]-k);
            res = min(res, high-low);
        }
        return res;
    }
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Dry Run
Input:

Code
nums = [1,3,6], k=3
Sorted: [1,3,6]

Initial diff = 6-1 = 5

i=0 → high=max(1+3,6-3)=max(4,3)=4, low=min(1+3,3-3)=min(4,0)=0 → diff=4

i=1 → high=max(3+3,6-3)=max(6,3)=6, low=min(1+3,6-3)=min(4,3)=3 → diff=3

Answer = 3 ✅

